metadata.name: FORMAT #78
metadata.description:
A generative animated artwork by Unruly Unroll, 2022.  
Custom HTML, JavaScript and GLSL code.

This artwork is responsive and the canvas will adapt to the size and orientation of the browser window.

Interaction on desktop :
- Press the 'SPACE' key to pause/unpause the animation.
- Press the 'S' key to save the current frame to a PNG file.  
- Press the 'F' key or double-click to switch to full screen mode.  
- Press the 'ESC' key to exit full screen mode.  

Interaction on mobile :
- Tap the screen to pause/unpause the animation.
- Double-tap the screen to switch to full screen mode.  
- Tap the back button to exit full screen mode.

@UnrulyUnroll

metadata.name: Happenings #219
metadata.description:
Inspired by the chaos and imperfectly beautiful dynamics of parenting and life, 'Happenings' is the embodiment of the messiness, the unexpected and playful experiences that allow for the greatest depths of connection with our children.

Our intention was to evoke our deepest and most personal feelings as parents of young ones navigating the challenges of the pandemic while immersing ourselves in the Web3 arena.

This collection is Jimena + Marcos‚Äô first generative art collection in the Tezos blockchain via FX Hash, and consists of 222 1/1 artworks created with javascript.

metadata.name: contrapuntos #412
metadata.description:
Musical counterpoint is to me an abstraction of the layered, intertwining rhythms of every activity we carry on in our lives. With a global tempo typically set in days, we fit all sorts of temporal structures where our joys and fears live and play out over the span of our lives. This series is a metaphorical transposition of the musical counterpoint into a visual space, sometimes with repeating patterns, sometimes with broken structures, sometimes isolated notes / hours / souls.

Artwork by Marcelo Soria-Rodr√≠guez, @msoriaro. Made with p5js & glsl.

metadata.name: Rebug #338
metadata.description:
A debug view of the underlying particulate algorithm of Atoms' Gaze and Quantum Folly. Refined as a gift for collectors.

Enjoy watching the structures form. Once it's fully rendered you can download a full resolution image of 3508 x 4961 px by ***double clicking/tapping***. At this size the piece is printable at A3 size at 300 dpi. If you're interested in acquiring a signed print please contact @KRANKARTA.

Created on Chrome desktop 103.0 on 2022-08-06 in javascript and GLSL. Results on other browsers/devices may vary.

metadata.name: color combinations #123
metadata.description:
the 'color combinations' series was developed as an exercise of combining colors from a single defined palette and the attempt to make all 15 selected colors being able to work within each other.

the constant pursuit for perfectionism made me design more than 200 tentatives of creating a perfect circle, and therefore the circle is the rarest output for the series.

i hope this series serves as a reference and inspire everyone out there.

2,340 possible combinations.
the closer the shape to the circle the rarer - ranging from 100% to 5%.
the bigger the shape the rarer - ranging from 30% to 20%.
beige and black colors are rarer - ranging from 100% to 5%

metadata.name: Richter #320
metadata.description:
Richter is the second collaboration of Richard Nadler and Leander Herzog, following their first project called Gerhard. A generative animation based on multiple layers of color and data, mixed, moved and painted over in realtime. Some fragments stick to the canvas while others get discarded to leave the existing layers visible, allowing a complex surface to emerge and build up over time.
 
Richter works with data from 4 of 24 highres images, 30mb in total. This is the maximum size fxhash allows for a project and three times more than Gerhard. Richard Nadler created stunning new textures, enabling more variation in composition and detail to emerge at much higher resolution. Leander Herzog created the code for the interplay between the layers, motion and interactions. Richter elevates the approach from Gerhard with new methods for the realtime rendering process and new features like offline-first caching. Both artists use different tools and are not aware of the details of each others process, meeting through the interface of pixels as data.
 
Richter is featured in the exhibition "Generative Abstraction" at Expanded.art in Berlin.
 
- Click to start a new layer of motion and color.
- Doubleclick to enter fullscreen.
- Press ‚Äús‚Äù to save the canvas.
- Append ?dpr=4 to the url to increase the resolution.
